timeline.bodyText:
The spawning of asynchronous tasks inside of other asynchronous tasks can be a real source of problems if you are trying to dispose the handler while it is getting initialized. I suggest wrapping the Thread fields in a CompletableFuture so that you have a way to prevent starting them in the event that dispose it called before your asynchronous task initialized them.
CompletableFuture<Thread> readThreadFuture;

public void initialize() {
  readThreadFuture = new CompletableFuture<>();
  readThreadFuture.thenAccept(Thread::start);

  Thread readerThread = new Thread(this::readerThreadJob, "Lutron reader");
  readerThread.setDaemon(true);

  executor.submit(() -> {
    ...
    readThreadFuture.complete(readerThread);
  });
}

public void dispose(){
  //if this completes the future the asynchronous 'complete()' will be ignored
  if(!readThreadFuture.cancel(false)){
     //failure to cancel means that the future completed first, so lets interrupt the thread then   
     readThreadFuture.thenAccept(thread -> thread.interrupt());
  }
}

In addition could you initialize your keepAliveJob inside of the initialize() method instead of doing it asynchronously? You could just make the keepAliveJob skip if the socket isn't ready yet.

